1-create a custom-commands file:

	sudo touch ~/.custom-commands

2-open the custom-commands file and create an alias for each custom command you wish:

	sudo vim ~/.custom-commands

	to create the custom commands use the following syntax:

		alias <custom-name>='<custom command>'

	i.e.
		alias lsa='ls -la'
		alias clsa='clear; ls -la'	#or 'clear; lsa'

		alias html='cd /var/www/html'

3-update the changes:

	source ~/.custom-commands

	(insert this line on your ~/.bashrc)
